  <!-- ── UNDERSTANDING LINK VALUE ── -->
  <section id="learn" class="bg-white py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-5">
        What Actually Determines The Value Of A Backlink
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-8 font-medium max-w-3xl">
        Not all backlinks are equal. These factors determine whether a link moves rankings or wastes budget.
      </p>

      <div class="divide-y divide-[#0A0F1E]/8 border border-[#0A0F1E]/8 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden mb-12" id="pi-acc-list-1">
        <div class="pi-acc-item">
          <button class="pi-acc-btn w-full flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-6 py-5 text-left bg-white hover:bg-[#F8F7FA] transition-colors" data-pi-index="0" type="button">
            <span class="pi-acc-question text-base font-semibold text-[#0A0F1E]">What is Domain Rating and why does it matter?</span>
            <svg class="pi-acc-chevron shrink-0 transition-transform duration-300 text-[#64748B]" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="pi-acc-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 bg-white">
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-3">Domain Rating is a metric developed by Ahrefs that scores a website's backlink profile strength on a scale of 0 to 100. Higher DR generally indicates a stronger domain. It's the most widely used proxy for link value, which is why higher-DR sites charge more.</p>
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">However, DR can be artificially inflated through link schemes — which is why it should never be the sole factor in evaluating a link. Always cross-reference with organic traffic, editorial quality, and topical relevance.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="pi-acc-item">
          <button class="pi-acc-btn w-full flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-6 py-5 text-left bg-white hover:bg-[#F8F7FA] transition-colors" data-pi-index="1" type="button">
            <span class="pi-acc-question text-base font-semibold text-[#0A0F1E]">Why traffic matters more than DR alone</span>
            <svg class="pi-acc-chevron shrink-0 transition-transform duration-300 text-[#64748B]" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="pi-acc-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 bg-white">
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-3">A site's organic traffic is a stronger indicator of genuine authority than its Domain Rating. Google's ranking systems have already validated a site that receives consistent organic traffic — it's earning real clicks from real search queries.</p>
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">BuzzStream's analysis found that 53% of DR71+ sites on marketplace databases have under 50,000 monthly organic traffic. The DR number suggests premium value; the traffic data tells a different story.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="pi-acc-item">
          <button class="pi-acc-btn w-full flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-6 py-5 text-left bg-white hover:bg-[#F8F7FA] transition-colors" data-pi-index="2" type="button">
            <span class="pi-acc-question text-base font-semibold text-[#0A0F1E]">What makes a link editorially valuable?</span>
            <svg class="pi-acc-chevron shrink-0 transition-transform duration-300 text-[#64748B]" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="pi-acc-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 bg-white">
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-3">An editorially valuable link is one placed by a journalist, editor, or content creator because it genuinely enhances their content — not because someone paid for it. These links appear in news articles, feature stories, expert roundups, and data-driven reporting.</p>
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">Google's algorithm leak revealed that the search engine evaluates links from high-click areas of sites that are updated frequently — characteristics of genuine editorial content on active publications.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="pi-acc-item">
          <button class="pi-acc-btn w-full flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-6 py-5 text-left bg-white hover:bg-[#F8F7FA] transition-colors" data-pi-index="3" type="button">
            <span class="pi-acc-question text-base font-semibold text-[#0A0F1E]">Dofollow vs nofollow in 2026</span>
            <svg class="pi-acc-chevron shrink-0 transition-transform duration-300 text-[#64748B]" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="pi-acc-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 bg-white">
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-3">Dofollow links pass ranking signals to the target page. Nofollow links include an attribute telling search engines not to pass credit. Most paid placements target dofollow links for the direct SEO benefit.</p>
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">In practice, the distinction has blurred since Google began treating nofollow as a "hint" rather than a directive in 2019. A nofollow link from a major publication still provides referral traffic, brand visibility, and entity recognition. A natural link profile contains both.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-lg md:text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink leading-snug mb-3 mt-4">Risk And Compliance</h3>
      <p class="text-xl text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-8 font-medium max-w-2xl">
        The cost of a link is not just the price you pay. It includes the risk you take.
      </p>

      <div class="divide-y divide-[#0A0F1E]/8 border border-[#0A0F1E]/8 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden mb-10" id="pi-acc-list-2">
        <div class="pi-acc-item">
          <button class="pi-acc-btn w-full flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-6 py-5 text-left bg-white hover:bg-[#F8F7FA] transition-colors" data-pi-index="4" type="button">
            <span class="pi-acc-question text-base font-semibold text-[#0A0F1E]">What Google considers a link scheme</span>
            <svg class="pi-acc-chevron shrink-0 transition-transform duration-300 text-[#64748B]" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="pi-acc-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 bg-white">
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-3">Google's spam policies classify several practices as link schemes: buying or selling links that pass PageRank, exchanging goods or services for links, and large-scale guest posting campaigns with keyword-rich anchor text.</p>
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">Both paid guest posts and paid niche edits fall within this definition. The practical risk depends on scale and detectability — a single placement is unlikely to trigger a penalty, but building a profile primarily through marketplace purchases creates a pattern Google's systems are designed to detect.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="pi-acc-item">
          <button class="pi-acc-btn w-full flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-6 py-5 text-left bg-white hover:bg-[#F8F7FA] transition-colors" data-pi-index="5" type="button">
            <span class="pi-acc-question text-base font-semibold text-[#0A0F1E]">The Helpful Content Update and marketplace sites</span>
            <svg class="pi-acc-chevron shrink-0 transition-transform duration-300 text-[#64748B]" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="pi-acc-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 bg-white">
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-3">Google's Helpful Content Update specifically targeted sites that exist primarily to host third-party content for SEO purposes. Many sites that accepted paid guest posts at scale were deindexed or severely demoted.</p>
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">Buyers who had invested in links on these sites found their backlink profiles devalued overnight with no recourse. Most marketplace services offer 6–12 month guarantees, but a replacement link on another marketplace site carries the same underlying risk.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="pi-acc-item">
          <button class="pi-acc-btn w-full flex items-center justify-between gap-4 px-6 py-5 text-left bg-white hover:bg-[#F8F7FA] transition-colors" data-pi-index="6" type="button">
            <span class="pi-acc-question text-base font-semibold text-[#0A0F1E]">Why earned editorial links carry zero penalty risk</span>
            <svg class="pi-acc-chevron shrink-0 transition-transform duration-300 text-[#64748B]" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="pi-acc-answer hidden px-6 pb-5 bg-white">
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-3">Links placed by journalists and editors through genuine editorial decisions are exactly what Google's ranking system was designed to reward. The link was not purchased, the publisher was not compensated, and the editorial decision was independent.</p>
            <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">There is no mechanism by which a genuine editorial link can trigger a penalty. The publication also carries near-zero deindexation risk — established media outlets are not targets for Google's spam enforcement.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-[#5D4FE0] rounded-r-2xl p-6 shadow-[0_4px_20px_-8px_rgba(10,15,30,0.08)]">
        <p class="text-3xl font-black text-[#5D4FE0] mb-1">+203%</p>
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-[#0A0F1E] mb-2">Increase in publisher-direct DR30 pricing, 2020–2024</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">Pricing collected direct from publishers has tripled over four years (FatRank industry benchmark). Agency-managed pricing has moved more slowly. The pressure is coming from the supply side.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── BOUGHT VS EARNED ── -->
  <section id="compare" class="py-16 md:py-24" style="background: #F8F7FA;">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-5">
        Paid Backlinks Vs Earned Editorial Placements
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-8 font-medium max-w-3xl">
        Every link in the marketplace data above is a bought link. Anyone with a budget can acquire them. The question is whether that builds a lasting advantage — or just a temporary one.
      </p>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-10">
        <!-- Bought -->
        <div class="bg-[#F1F5F9] rounded-2xl p-8 border border-[#0A0F1E]/8">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[#DC2626] mb-4">Bought links</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-6">A commodity. Your competitors can buy the same link on the same site for the same price. The publisher's incentive is the fee, not the quality of your content.</p>
          <ul class="space-y-3">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><X size={15} class="text-[#94A3B8] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />Available to any competitor with budget</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><X size={15} class="text-[#94A3B8] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />15–25% annual attrition rate</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><X size={15} class="text-[#94A3B8] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />Host site deindexation risk</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><X size={15} class="text-[#94A3B8] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />Classified as link scheme by Google</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><X size={15} class="text-[#94A3B8] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />No brand recognition or audience exposure</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><X size={15} class="text-[#94A3B8] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />95% of sites fail basic quality filters</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <!-- Earned -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-8 border-2 border-[#5D4FE0]/20 shadow-[0_4px_20px_-8px_rgba(10,15,30,0.08)]">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[#15803D] mb-4">Earned links</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-6">A signal that your brand has something worth covering. Requires a genuine story — original data, expert insight, or newsworthy commentary. Your competitors cannot buy this.</p>
          <ul class="space-y-3">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569] font-medium"><Check size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />Cannot be replicated by competitors with budget alone</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569] font-medium"><Check size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />Avg. link lifespan 10+ years on established publications</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569] font-medium"><Check size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />Zero deindexation risk on editorial sites</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569] font-medium"><Check size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />Exactly what Google's algorithm rewards</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569] font-medium"><Check size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />Brand mentions, expert positioning, real audience</li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569] font-medium"><Check size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" />Compounds — each placement builds authority</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Earned links are not free. They require investment in creating something worth covering — a data study, expert commentary, a newsworthy angle. They take longer to materialise than a marketplace purchase, and you don't control the exact anchor text or placement. But these constraints are features: they're what makes earned links defensible, durable, and valued by search engines.
      </p>
      <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-8">
        Digital PR makes the most sense for businesses where a single lead, client, or conversion justifies the campaign investment. If your average customer is worth thousands, a $3,500 campaign that delivers 8–12+ earned placements — each one building lasting authority and brand recognition — pays for itself quickly. For businesses selling low-ticket products with thin margins, marketplace links at lower DR tiers may be a more practical starting point.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-[#5D4FE0] rounded-r-2xl p-6 shadow-[0_4px_20px_-8px_rgba(10,15,30,0.08)]">
        <p class="text-3xl font-black text-[#5D4FE0] mb-2">$44 vs $250</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">Annual cost per link when accounting for lifespan. A $437 earned link lasting 10+ years costs $44/year. A $500 bought link with a two-year effective lifespan costs $250/year.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── AI SEARCH BRIDGE ── -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-white">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
    <div class="mb-10">
      <div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-brand font-medium mb-3">AI Search Context</div>
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-5">
        Why Backlink Pricing Matters For AI Search Visibility
      </h2>
    </div>

    <div class="prose prose-lg text-body max-w-none space-y-6 leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        Every data point on this page measures the same thing: the cost of a signal that used to tell search engines which brands to surface. The assumption behind buying that signal was that Google would read it, weigh it, and rank you accordingly.
      </p>
      <p>
        That assumption is now splitting in two. Google still reads links, but an increasing share of commercial intent now resolves inside AI systems — ChatGPT, Perplexity, Google's AI Overviews, Claude — that decide which brands to mention based on different evidence. They read editorial coverage on authority publishers. They read citation context, not anchor text. They read whether your brand appears inside answers humans trust, not whether it appears inside backlink indexes bots crawl.
      </p>
      <p>
        A DR50 marketplace link on a traffic-light site was always a questionable investment for Google rankings. It's worthless for AI answer surfaces. The sites AI systems cite are a different population from the sites link marketplaces sell access to, and the gap is widening as AI answer engines refine which sources they trust.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the mechanism behind citation equity: the editorial coverage on real publishers that accumulates as a brand signal across both search and AI systems. It is what our campaigns are built to earn. The pricing data above is useful context for anyone comparing options, but it describes a market that's solving yesterday's problem.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-muted italic">
        For the full argument and evidence, see <a href="/resources/citation-equity-vs-link-building" class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2">Citation equity vs link building</a>. For background on how AI systems choose which brands to surface, see <a href="/resources/ai-search-visibility" class="text-brand hover:text-brand-dark underline underline-offset-2">our AI search visibility guide</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

  <!-- ── METHODOLOGY ── -->
  <section id="methodology" class="py-16 md:py-24" style="background: #F8F7FA;">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-brand font-medium mb-3">Methodology</div>
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink leading-tight mb-5">
        How This Data Was Collected
      </h2>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-[#0A0F1E]/8 p-8 shadow-[0_4px_20px_-8px_rgba(10,15,30,0.08)] mb-8">
        <p class="text-base text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-6">The Cost of Authority: 2026 Backlink Pricing Index aggregates pricing data from multiple independent marketplace studies and live platform data:</p>
        <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><ArrowRight size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" /><span><strong class="text-[#0A0F1E]">BuzzStream (2025)</strong> — Analysis of 26,000+ guest post sites from a major vendor database, with quality tiering by traffic and DR</span></li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><ArrowRight size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" /><span><strong class="text-[#0A0F1E]">Adsy (2025)</strong> — Pricing analysis across 37,542 publisher websites</span></li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><ArrowRight size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" /><span><strong class="text-[#0A0F1E]">Serpzilla (2026)</strong> — Live marketplace data from thousands of guest post and niche edit listings</span></li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><ArrowRight size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" /><span><strong class="text-[#0A0F1E]">Linkhouse (2026)</strong> — Validated against live pricing from 76,861 publisher listings across 25 languages</span></li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><ArrowRight size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" /><span><strong class="text-[#0A0F1E]">Additional platforms</strong> — Collaborator, Getfluence, WhitePress, GuestPostLinks, Bazoom, and LinkPublishers</span></li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><ArrowRight size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" /><span><strong class="text-[#0A0F1E]">Service providers</strong> — Published pricing from 10+ named agencies and services</span></li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><ArrowRight size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" /><span><strong class="text-[#0A0F1E]">Wayback Machine (2020–2026)</strong> — Primary-source pricing snapshots across FATJOE, Searcharoo, Loganix, RhinoRank, and The HOTH, extracted via the Internet Archive CDX API. 104 observations, audit trail preserved.</span></li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><ArrowRight size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" /><span><strong class="text-[#0A0F1E]">FatRank industry cost study (2024)</strong> — Cross-network pricing analysis from an investor in multiple link-building platforms, providing publisher-direct vs agency-managed cost comparison.</span></li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-sm text-[#475569]"><ArrowRight size={15} class="text-[#5D4FE0] shrink-0 mt-0.5" /><span><strong class="text-[#0A0F1E]">Vendor-published review articles (2020–2026)</strong> — Dated third-party reviews citing then-current vendor pricing tables, used to corroborate and fill gaps in Wayback coverage.</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-3">All prices converted to USD at March 2026 exchange rates. Vendor markup estimates based on BuzzStream's methodology. Quality filtering follows BuzzStream's criteria: minimum 1,000 monthly organic traffic and minimum DR 40.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed mb-3">For the longitudinal dataset, one representative Wayback snapshot per year was selected per vendor (closest to mid-year) and parsed for tier pricing. DR/DA tiers are treated as equivalent since major vendors switched labeling conventions mid-window without changing the underlying product. LinksThatRank was excluded from the longitudinal chart because their pricing is rendered client-side; Wayback captures only the empty shell. The HOTH was excluded because their SKU mix changed substantially across years. Raw dataset available on request.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-[#475569] leading-relaxed">This index will be updated annually. Corrections or data contributions welcome at <a href="mailto:contact@ranking-atlas.com" class="inline-link">contact@ranking-atlas.com</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Cite box -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-[#0A0F1E]/8 p-6 shadow-[0_4px_20px_-8px_rgba(10,15,30,0.08)] relative">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-[#0A0F1E] mb-3">Cite this resource</p>
        <code id="citeText" class="block font-mono text-xs text-[#475569] leading-relaxed bg-[#F8F7FA] rounded-lg p-4 pr-20">Ranking Atlas. "The Cost of Authority: 2026 Backlink Pricing Index." ranking-atlas.com/resources/the-cost-of-authority. Published March 2026.</code>
        <button id="copyBtn"
          class="absolute top-6 right-6 bg-[#F1F5F9] hover:bg-[#E2E8F0] border border-[#0A0F1E]/10 rounded-lg px-3 py-1.5 text-xs font-medium text-[#475569] transition-colors">
          Copy
        </button>
